The paper deals with the design and analysis of a kinetic data structure for maintaining all the nearest neighbors of a set of moving points in $\mathbb{R}^d$. This involves maintaining the edges of the Semi-Yao graph, a sparse graph whose edge set includes the pairs of nearest neighbors as a subset. Therefore, the paper is likely to belong to the Computational Geometry (cs.CG) sub-category. Additionally, the paper proposes a new technique that provides the first KDS for the Semi-Yao graph in $\mathbb{R}^d$, which suggests that it could also belong to the Data Structures and Algorithms (cs.DS) sub-category. The paper also mentions the use of slow-growing functions, which could indicate that it belongs to the Discrete Mathematics (cs.DM) sub-category. The paper deals with maintaining nearest neighbors, which is a common problem in Machine Learning and Artificial Intelligence, suggesting that it could also belong to the Social and Information Networks (cs.SI) sub-category. Finally, the paper mentions a KDS for maintenance of all the $(1+\epsilon)$-nearest neighbors, which could indicate that it belongs to the Information Theory (cs.IT) sub-category.
